<topic id='business_definition_local_authority.description'>
  <title>Description</title>
  <titlealts>
    <searchtitle>NHS Business Definition: Local Authority - Description</searchtitle>
  </titlealts>
  <body>
  <div>
      <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authority</xref>
 is an 
              <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_organisation">ORGANISATION</xref>.        </p>
      <p>The structure of local government varies from area to area in England. In some areas there are two layers or tiers:</p>
      <ol>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>
a 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_county">County</xref>
 or Shire Council as the upper tier and                    </p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>
a 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition" keyref="business_definition_district">District</xref>, Borough or City Council as the lower tier.                    </p>
            </div>
         </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
In other areas there is just a single tier made up of a '<xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authority</xref>'. 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authorities</xref>
 may have adopted any of these names. In London each borough is a Unitary Administration with a status similar to that of 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_metropolitan_district">Metropolitan Districts</xref>, with the London Assembly providing strategic, city-wide government.        </p>
      <p>
A 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authority</xref>
 is responsible for a range of services for both individuals and business which include:        </p>
      <ul>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Health Services</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Social Services</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Education</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Planning</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Waste disposal, recycling and collection</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Trading standards</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Roads, highways and transportation</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Housing</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Environmental Health</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Approving planning applications</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>Enforcing health, safety, environment and trading standards requirements etc</p>
            </div>
         </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
         <b>From April 2013:</b>
      </p>
      <ul>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>
each 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                        keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authority</xref>
 in England has a fully operational 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                        keyref="business_definition_health_and_wellbeing_board">Health and Wellbeing Board</xref>
               </p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                     keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authorities</xref>
               <p>
 in partnership with 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                        keyref="business_definition_clinical_commissioning_group">Clinical Commissioning Groups</xref>
 are responsible for commissioning the majority of NHS 
                                <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_service">SERVICES</xref>
 for 
                                <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_patient">PATIENTS</xref>
 within their local communities                    </p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                     keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authorities</xref>
               <p> are responsible for protecting and improving health and wellbeing.</p>
            </div>
         </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
For the purposes of the 
              <xref outputclass="supportingInformation"
               keyref="supporting_definition_organisation_data_service">Organisation Data Service</xref>, the definition for a '<xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authority</xref>' 
              <xref outputclass="class" keyref="class_organisation">ORGANISATION</xref>
  is based on (but is not exactly the same as) the definition given within the Local Government Act, as follows:        </p>
      <p>
A "
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authority</xref>", in relation to England is:        </p>
      <ul>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>a County Council</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>a District Council</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>
a 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                        keyref="business_definition_london_borough">London Borough</xref>
 Council                    </p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>
the Common Council of the City of London in its capacity as a 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                        keyref="business_definition_local_authority">Local Authority</xref>
               </p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>the Council of the Isles of Scilly</p>
            </div>
         </li>
         <li>
            <div>
               <p>
a 
                                <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
                        keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authority</xref>
               </p>
            </div>
         </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
Across Wales, there is a single tier system of 
              <xref outputclass="businessDefinition"
               keyref="business_definition_unitary_authority">Unitary Authorities</xref>
 (Councils).        </p>
      <p>
         <i>
Note that the Scotland Councils and Northern Ireland Councils are not included within the 
                  <xref outputclass="supportingInformation"
                  keyref="supporting_definition_organisation_data_service">Organisation Data Service</xref>
 data set.            </i>
      </p>
  </div>
